Sentiment Analysis on Twitter Data using Logistic Regression
This project demonstrates how to build a sentiment analysis model using the Sentiment140 Twitter dataset. The model is trained using Logistic Regression, and it classifies tweets into positive and negative sentiments after preprocessing and vectorization.

ğŸ“ Project Overview
This sentiment analysis system leverages machine learning to determine whether a given tweet expresses a positive or negative sentiment. The Sentiment140 dataset contains 1.6 million pre-labeled tweets, providing a robust foundation for training and evaluating the model.

ğŸ“‚ Dataset
Source: Kaggle - Sentiment140 Dataset

The dataset contains 1,600,000 tweets.

Original labels: 0 = Negative, 4 = Positive â†’ converted to 0 = Negative, 1 = Positive

Only the tweet text and sentiment label are used for model training.

ğŸ“Œ Features
Preprocessing: Cleaning text, lowercasing, removing stopwords, stemming

Vectorization using TF-IDF

Train-test split with sklearn

Model training with LogisticRegression

Accuracy evaluation on both training and testing data

Model serialization using pickle

Prediction on new tweets

